rize agents as a product of the 1950s, but Kemper revises the record to show how agents emerged from the primordial film industry during the late 1920s and carved themselves a permanent niche. Through case studies of key figures like Myron Selznick and Charles Feldman, we see that the agent's character and social relationships functioned within a business structure-a good reputation and powerful connections were his most precious assets. With wit and precision, Kemper locates Hollywood agents at the crossroads of talent and profit, and captures their central and enduring role in the burgeoning film industry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMotion picture industryxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos AngelesxLos Angeles- HollywoodxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aMotion picture industryzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTheatrical agenciesxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aTheatrical agencieszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTheatrical agentsxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aTheatrical agentszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520944749.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles